value.value: The pleuron that is articulated with the fore leg, connected dorsolaterally (anterolaterally) with the pronotum and ventrally (posteriorly) with the prosternum.
The area that is located between the propodeal foramen and metacoxal foramina.
The carina that is located on the propodeum.
The foramen that is located on the metapectal-propodeal complex in which the petiole is positioned.
The articular process that is located on the margin of the propodeal-metapectal complex around the propodeal foramen and bears the metasomal condyle of the propodeum.
The second abdominal sternal muscle that originates ventral to the metaphragma and inserts on the anterodorsal margin of the abdominal sternite 2.
The second abdominal tergal muscle that arises from the abdominal tergum 1 and inserts on the abdominal tergum 2.
The mesofurcal muscle that arises from the prospinasternum and inserts on the mesofurca.
The notch that separates the basisternum from the furcasternum in the prosternum.
The procoxal muscle that arises from the prosternum and inserts on the procoxa.
The sclerite that is connected posteriorly to the propleuron and bears the prodiscrimen and the profurca.
The thoracic segment that is located between the head and the mesothorax is composed of the pronotum, the propectus and the fore leg.
The tibial spur that is located on the fore leg, is curved and together with the probasitarsus forms the strigil.
The gonostyle-parossiculal muscle that arises proximally from the lateral part of the gonostipes and inserts on the proximal part of the parossiculus.

The dorsal gonostyle/volsella complex penisvalval muscle that arises proximodorsally from the gonostyle/volsella complex and inserts on the penisvalva distally of the site of insertion of the distodorsal gononstyle/volsella complex-penisvalva muscle.
The apodeme that is located laterally on the proximal margin of the cupula and corresponds to the site of insertion of the second lateral 9th sterno-cupulal muscle.

The ventral gonostyle/volsella complex-penisvalval muscle that arises ventromedially from the gonostyle/volsella complex, inserts on the proximal end of the penisvalva and is oriented proximodorsally.
The projection that is medial and located apically on the penisvalva.
The flange that extends along the dorsal margin of the dorsal mesopostnotal flange.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of the axillary sclerites and the humeral plate.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of the meso- and metathorax and if the latter is fused with, the first abdominal tergum.
The depression that is point-like, without a flat bottom, and occurs in areas of punctate surface sculpture.
The area that is located posteriorly on the tergum of the last externally visible segment of the abdomen.
The wing vein that is connected to the second axillary sclerite and extends posterior to the subcosta.
The area that is located proximally on the scape, is limited distally by a constriction and bears proximally the basal knob.
The wing vein that connects the radial vein with the medial vein.
The area that extends external to the dorsal ramus of the first valvula.
The area that is located proximally on valvulae and is connected to the valvifers.
The wing region anterior to the vannal fold containing the costa, subcosta, radius, medius, cubitus, and postcubitus.
The anatomical system that is involved in reproduction.
The epipharyngeal muscle that arises from the clypeus and inserts on the epipharyngeal wall.
The hypopharyngeal muscle that arises from the upper face and inserts on the proximolateral process of the sitophore.
The ridge that extends along the ventral surface of the second valvula that is partially enclosed by the aulax.
The apodeme that is elongate.
The carina that extends along the margin or edge of a sclerite.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of repeated units of anatomical structures.
The row that is composed of impressions.
The row that is composed of setae.
The carina that is irregularly non-linear.
The anatomical space that is situated posteriorly in the salivarium, proximal to the insertion of the dilatators.
The area that is adjacent to the proximal end of the salivary duct and corresponds to the site of insertion of the dorsal and ventral premento-salivarial muscles.
The sensillum with a scale-like cuticular component.
The antennal segment that is proximal to the pedicel and is connected to the head via the radicle.
The area of the cuticle that is less flexible than adjacent conjunctivae.
The setiferous patch that is used for pollen storage.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of antennal scrobes.
The area that is impressed and is for the reception or concealment of another sclerite.
The area that is located on the sclerite and that is composed of repetitive anatomical structures.
The apodeme that originates from the scutoscutellar ridge and fuses with the posterior part of the mesoscutellum.
